The paper proposes a data-driven method for 3D shape design using a generative model learned from a corpus of existing designs. This involves the use of unsupervised variational autoencoder-decoder architecture, which is commonly used in computer graphics (cs.GR) and computer vision (cs.CV) for image and shape synthesis. The approach also involves optimization for achieving prescribed functional goals, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the paper discusses the use of physics simulations, which is relevant to the sub-category of social and information networks (cs.SI) that deals with modeling and simulation of complex systems.
